The Paso Doble is a theatrical Latin dance with Spanish and French origins. It is a dramatic dance that tells a story through sharp, staccato movements, striking body poses, and flamenco style footwork. The Paso Doble is a passionate dance based on a Spanish bullfight. The leader represents the proud Spanish matador and the woman or follower is the Matador‚Äôs cape. The follower will sometimes also represent the bull, picador or flamenco dancer. Paso Doble music was originally played for the entrance of the matador into the bull-fighting ring. In Spainish tradition dating back to the 18<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;century, it was also known as ‚ÄúEl Soleo‚Äù. Although the Paso Doble is based on a Spanish tradition, it‚Äôs believed that the dance was created in Southern France where they tried to portray the theatrics of the Spanish bullfight.

The name of the dance, ‚ÄúPaso Doble‚Äù is believed to trace back to a French military march with a similar name, ‚ÄúPaso Redoble.‚Äù The Paso Redoble was a march with a 2/4 beat and about 130 beats or steps per minute. Even today the Paso Doble dance is characterized by it‚Äôs marching-like steps and is now the fastest Latin ballroom dance. Every second step of the marching dance is emphasized, and this may also be why the dance is called ‚ÄúPaso Doble‚Äù or translated to English ‚Äúdouble step‚Äù.

Paso Doble received the coin term ‚Äúdance of the master‚Äù because of the boldness and beaming pride expressed by the ‚Äútorero‚Äù in the dance. The strength and decisiveness of the lead was interpreted as that of a master. The female follow, much like in Flamenco dance, also dances with a kind of self-confidence, beaming elegance and strength at the same time. The Paso Doble adopted some elements of the figures, steps, and character of Flamenco dancing.

